As discussed in the chapter, a two-step dividend growth rate refers to a model wherein the dividend undergoes a first stage where the growth is usually unstable and the second stage where there is constant growth on the dividend. 

In this model, the current price of the share is given as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{P}_0&=\dfrac{\text{D}_0\times(1+\text{g}_1)}{(1+\text{R})}+\dfrac{\text{D}_0\times(1+\text{g}_1)^2}{(1+\text{R})^2}+\cdots+ \dfrac{\text{D}_0\times(1+\text{g}_1)^t}{(1+\text{R})^t}
\end{aligned}$$

Where,

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{P}_0&=\text{Current price of the stock}\\
\text{D}_0&=\text{Current dividend}\\
\text{g}_1&=\text{Growth rate at first stage}\\
\text{R}&=\text{Required rate of return}\\
\text{t}&=\text{Time}
\end{aligned}$$

If the growth rate at the first stage and the required rate of return are equal, then we can use $\text{g}_1=\text{R}$. Substituting this in the equation, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{P}_0&=\dfrac{\text{D}_0\times(1+\text{R})}{(1+\text{R})}+\dfrac{\text{D}_0\times(1+\text{R})^2}{(1+\text{R})^2}+\cdots +\dfrac{\text{D}_0\times(1+\text{R})^t}{(1+\text{R})^t}
\end{aligned}$$

We can then cancel $(1+\text{R})$ from both numerator and denominator which will leave us with:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{P}_0&=\text{D}_0+\text{D}_0+\cdots+\text{D}_0
\end{aligned}$$

Or simply,

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{P}_0&=\text{D}_0\times t
\end{aligned}$$

Where $t$ is the time.

If we then substitute this to the formula for the current share price using the two-step dividend growth model, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{P}_0&=(\text{D}_0\times t)+\dfrac{\text{D}_0(1+\text{g}_1)^t(1+\text{g}_2)}{\text{R}-\text{g}_2}
\end{aligned}$$
